    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 97,
    "last_activity_date" : 1623166788,
    "last_edit_date" : 1623166788,
    "creation_date" : 1329774582,
    "answer_id" : 9368930,
    "question_id" : 9368764,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Look into <a href=\"https://github.com/DimitrisAndreou/memory-measurer\" rel=\"noreferrer\">https://github.com/DimitrisAndreou/memory-measurer</a>.<br />\nGuava uses it internally, and <code>ObjectGraphMeasurer</code> is especially straightforward to use out-of-the-box, without any special command-line arguments.</p>\n<pre><code>import objectexplorer.ObjectGraphMeasurer;\n\npublic class Measurer {\n\n  public static void main(String[] args) {\n    Set&lt;Integer&gt; hashset = new HashSet&lt;Integer&gt;();\n    Random random = new Random();\n    int n = 10000;\n    for (int i = 1; i &lt;= n; i++) {\n      hashset.add(random.nextInt());\n    }\n    System.out.println(ObjectGraphMeasurer.measure(hashset));\n  }\n}\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
